site: UC Davis Arboretum: Shields Oak Grove: Grid #9-C1; Shields Oak Grove Tree #260
OrigSourceInfo: Various oak species (Quercus) collected in the fall of 1966 by McIntyre, Hildreth and Gankin in Panama, Costa Rica, Nicaragua, Honduras, El Savador Guatemala. Identifiexd by J. M. Collecting_Extracting notes: Chose 260 over 259 because it gets more sun & can move easily to reach leaves.  Could not get to 3rd trunk due to brush.  It's hard to see what's growing from what.  Leaves for DNA were pulled from the branches of the trunk with the 260 tag.  There are alot of brush (new trees?/ shoots) growing at base of tree.   Leaves for voucher were pulled off other trunk w/ Q. greggii label.   I didn't pull from "3rd" trunk because it was hard to tell if there are 2 trees there (1 trunk & a 2 trunk one), or if it's one tree. Used possible gps coordinates in ArcMap  and compared to Davis maps to determine tree qualifier .

Site: Schenley Park on the edge of the Carnegie Mellon University, Pittsburgh, Allegheny County, Pennsylvania, U.S.A.  "  U.S.A.StateCountyFrom Terrence E. Hanlon, Hanlon Electric Company       I was going down your list of oaks in your collection and noticed you have some Quercus Cerris (523-2000) aquired through the international oak society of unknown origin. If those acorns were acquired at the seed exchange at the 2000 convention held in Ashville they were in all likelihood donated by me. The seed source for those acorns is Schenley Park on the edge of the Carnegie Mellon University campus in Pittsburgh Pa. The planting of these trees date back to the early 1900's and may have been donated by the Carnegies as by their proximity to the oldest CMU campus buildings and as A Q.Cerris of the same approximate age survives near the ruin/foundation of the Carnegie Mansion near the Phipps Conservatory garden center."
Project: MOR RAD sequencing of LC Quercus collection.

determinationNotes: Completely glabrous on upper surface. Unlike the true Q laeta, which has obvious and abundant white papillae on undersurface of leaf; moreover, the glandular vermicular hairs are not right for Q laeta. In this and relatives, the final-order veins surround an island of whitish cells that are clearly set off from the darker (green) veinlets; when papillae are present, they hide the veinlets. The presence of the papillae and lack of vermicular glandular hairs is taken to be evidence for Q laeta.
Project: Phylogeny of the oaks of the Americas: Diversification of an ecologically important clade across the tropical-temperate divide. (2012-2015 NSF Grant, DEB 114648)
EXTRACTION LABELING: Quercus laeta, SPMCODE: QUE002001, collection#: 2017112
